European inflation slid into food
Accelerated inflation in the euro area is primarily due to the rapid rise in food prices.
The price increase in November has been higher than expected in the 13 countries of the euro zone, registering - after 2.6 percent in October - an annual inflation of 3.1 percent, announced the Statistical Office of the Union based in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts were only 3 percent likely, Bloomberg said.
The European Central Bank (ECB), unlike the U.S., British and Canadian issuing banks, did not cut basic interest on the pretext that the decline, coupled with rising commodity prices and reduced forced unemployment, would trigger an inflation spiral.
The ECB wants to keep the inflation rate below, but at least close to two percent.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in trap 22: "we have to negotiate" on inflation so that later it does not have to intervene on this issue.
Inflation of 3.3 percent, recorded in Germany, beat the record of twelve years; while in Spain it increased from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
Inflation soared in the euro area as a result of rampant food and energy prices.
Wheat forward prices rose by 88 percent and soybeans reached their highest level since 1973.
Similarly, much more had to be paid in 2007 for vegetable oil and dairy products.
The price of crude oil on the world market increased this year by 52 percent, reaching almost $100 a barrel last month.
According to the ECB, inflation in 2008 will jump from the current 2.1 percent to 2.5 percent, while by 2009 it will already decrease to 1.9 percent.
According to analysts, annual inflation will remain around 3 percent over the next 3 or 4 months, but the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, the ECB is expected to double interest rates in 2008.
Gallup predicts a government crisis
After a long stalemate, by early December the support of the Alliance of Young Democrats increased significantly, reaching its highest level since 2002, while the Gallup never before experienced such a low level - 13 percent - in the case of the socialists.
The difference in the case of the safe voters of the parties - due to the greater firmness of the opposition voters - would mean a support of more than two-thirds (71 percent) against the support of one-fifth for the socialists (20 percent).
According to the poll, the Democratic Forum and the Alliance of Free Democrats would not reach even the limit necessary to have any parliamentary seat: their support within the entire population is two percent.
Among safe voters there are one percent more supporters on both sides.
The economic environment continued to deteriorate even compared to the previous lowest point - it has never been so high, 41 percent of those who judged the economic situation of the country especially bad, while another 46 percent believe that the situation is quite bad.
Families, after the more hopeful expectations of spring and summer, are now more pessimistic about changing their own economic situation.
As far as next year is concerned, the majority of the population expects the situation to deteriorate and only a tenth expects an improvement.
In December, 71 percent of respondents, higher than any previous Gallup poll, said the prime minister performed poorly rather than well.
13 percent of the respondents trust or trust Ferenc Gyurcsány very much, while Viktor Orbán has the support of 38 percent of the respondents.
54 percent of the population do not trust the head of government at all and 27 percent do not trust the president of the Young Democrats Alliance.
One of the indicators of the configuration of the political situation is that, what proportion of society thinks that it is possible to control the discontent experienced in front of the person of the Head of Government without a change of government.
While after the riots of October last year 35% estimated that it would be desirable to keep the government and the head of government in power, currently this proportion is only 20%, while the relative majority (33%) believes that the only solution is to hold new elections.
Interest in the referendum is characterized by the fact that 60 percent of respondents to the question about participation answered that they would safely participate and another 20 percent said they are likely to participate.
By comparison, only 55 per cent of the population would surely participate in "a general election to be held this Sunday" and another 15 per cent believe their participation is likely. Based on the current intentions of the voters there is no doubt about the result of the popular consultation.
74 percent of the population would disapprove of the payment of school fees, 79 percent of the service of medical consultations and 84 percent of hospital care.
If we look at these proportions only among the safe participants in the referendum, 81, 84 and 89 percent of voters would reject the introduction of the rights to study, the payment for medical consultations and hospital care.
The most expensive is the Auchan, the Tesco has quintupled its prices
The average increase in the price level of 16 percent was maintained by the hypermarkets of the Budaörs gold trade triangle, with the difference that this year VAT has not been increased.
Article by Napi Gazdaság
This year, the Napi newspaper’s usual Christmas basket also increased by an average of 16 percent in the Budaörs gold trade triangle, but in all hypermarkets growth was well above 1,000 HUF.
As prices in food supermarkets had already "shot" in December last year, so there was no drastic percentage increase compared to the high starting point.
However, it is obviously frightening for consumers the fact that what they were able to buy last year at a price well below nine thousand HUF, today they can not do it even for ten thousand.
The Napi basket in the studied hypermarkets exceeded the psychological limit of ten thousand HUF with a minimum of 91 HUF.
And the highest value basket was 10,573 HUF.
(in 2003 that basket cost HUF 6800.)
The price of Unicum liquor and fish remained almost at the level of the previous year, but there was a sharp increase in turkey breast, walnut and poppy seed steak.
The price of wheat flour and bread followed the data of the Central Bureau of Statistics, although in the Auchan we have also found a kilo of bread for the price of 139 HUF.
Competition did not reduce the price of the product to less than 200 HUF.
It was also surprising in this shop that the price of Coca-Cola with a redeemable two-liter bottle cost less than 200 HUF, so that this product, even with the price of the bottle, cost only 257 HUF.
However, in Napi Auchan’s basket it was the most expensive, while Cora was the cheapest.
According to our calculations, with respect to last year’s Christmas prices, Cora increased by 15 percent, while Tesco and Auchan increased by about 18 percent the prices listed in Napi’s basket.
Comparing the values of last year’s most expensive basket with that of this year’s cheapest basket, the difference has been 12 percent, while the growth between last year’s cheapest and this year’s most expensive basket has been 21 percent.
The average growth was 1480 HUF.
Last year, the average price growth was 1206 HUF, so during Christmas time last year the price was increased by VAT.
It was precisely this process that shattered trade, supermarkets were visibly unable to decide on the price margin to be applied to each product and to calculate the effect of the price change on consumption.
(If the merchant misplans the speed of a product’s circulation, he may lose a significant profit in the margin that fits the sales volume.)
The increase in the price of the Napi basket reached such extremes as a result of the increase in VAT, that the most expensive was higher by 1720 HUF than the value recorded in 2006, while in the cheapest the difference was only 844 HUF.
This year there were no such extremes, since the highest price now has been 1630 HUF more than last year and the cheapest also increased with 1284 HUF.
Comparing the two holiday seasons, there was a catastrophic growth in prices in less than 20 months, in hypermarkets the price of consumer necessities grew more than 30 percent.
(However, this does not necessarily confirm the figures of the Central Bureau of Statistics: this office, in the case of some basic necessities, recorded in the 12-month interval a price increase of more than 30 percent.
So, for example, in addition to wheat, also in the case of egg.)
According to the Napi basket, in the latter case this seems almost impossible, because in the price of this product that was quite expensive and last year compared to the base, there was registered, in the worst case, only a 10 percent increase in prices.
According to all the indices, flour suppliers have a stronger position than egg suppliers, being able to impose the drastic increase in prices even on multinationals.
Hypermarkets do not complain in the gold trading triangle, they constantly talk about positive results.
According to our experiences, most consumers in the three stores visited are no longer interested in prices.
Of all the products they buy large quantities, taking by pallets the preserved food.
On Wednesday morning, large queues were formed in front of the boxes in all three stores because the number of customers suddenly increased.
However, we have information that inside the country the sales volumes are lower, many multinationals complain to the survey institutes because the incomes are below their plans and not only in the case of food, but also in the case of household appliances.
Many hospitals save money with disinfectants
This year, several thousand infections caused primarily by the improper application of antibiotics have been reported in hospitals.
The prevailing hygiene conditions in hospitals, the overcrowding of beds and the overload of staff do not favor the control of infections - says the doctor-department head of the National Center of Epidemiology.
In many hospitals, even disinfectants are saved.
Not long ago, an MRSA infection was diagnosed in the trauma department of János Hospital.
In a man hospitalized after a serious accident, the presence of antibiotic-resistant bacteria was detected.
The patient was isolated.
The same type of infection occurred in this same hospital earlier this year.
One injured in a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital and the same patient soon after had to return to the hospital as a result of the MRSA infection and since then has not been able to perform a major surgical intervention because of the presence of the bacteria in his body.
As of December 10 of this year, 1094 cases of hospital infection caused by multidrug-resistant agents have been registered in the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System, said Karolina Böröcz, chief medical officer of the National Center for Epidemiology.
This means that in hospitals this number of infections caused by multi-resistant agents has been recorded, for the rest there is no information.
About two-thirds of infections (683 cases) are due to MRSA, i.e. methicillin-oxacillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus.
A third of humans carry Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their nose without causing any disease.
SA infections (e.g., throat inflammation, tonsillitis, skin infections, wound infections) react well to antibiotics and are easy to treat.
However, once antibiotics are exaggerated or improperly applied, bacteria that normally react well to antibiotics become highly antibiotic-resistant bacteria and quickly spread in inadequate hospital conditions.
They can cause serious hospital infections, such as wound infections or sepsis, primarily in patients with transient or chronic immunodeficiency, patients with the weakened body, the elderly or people of low weight.
In the opinion of the doctor-director of János Hospital there is nothing special about MRSA infection, these infections are daily in hospitals.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, the MRSA is only absent - said Tibor Nyulasi - where its presence is not examined.
Resistant to antibiotics
“These patients are isolated, nurses attend them in rubber gloves and masks and there are the right antibiotics for their treatment,” said Tibor Nyulasi.
Hospitalized patients are screened for the presence of MRSA in their body, but even this cannot prevent infection in all cases.
It's not fashionable to take samples
It would be possible to prevent MRSA hospital infections in most cases, however the current national hospital circumstances do not favour the prevention of the formation and contagion with multi-resistant pathogens - says Karolina Böröcz.
Because this infection occurs primarily in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should examine hospitalized patients and immediately isolate those who carry MRSA in their bodies.
However, microbiological sampling is not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
This is also because the National Health Fund does not fund these medical examinations.
So most cases come to light when MRSA infections already occur visible in the patient, said the doctor-department head of the epidemiological center.
The European Union makes rigorous orders for the application of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also national directives to treat infections and pathological conditions.
Antibiotic therapy should be targeted, i.e. microbiological tests should be done to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always meet this requirement.
Microbiological sampling is even less common in the case of ambulant patients or in basic care," said Karolina Böröcz.
Save money with disinfectants
Scientific experiments have shown that in most cases MRSA is transmitted from one patient to another through healthcare personnel.
Therefore, hand washing, the use of rubber gloves and masks play a very important role, however, also in this sense considerable faults are experienced in hospitals.
MRSA is transmitted by droplet transmission and direct contact between people, however in national hospital circumstances it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
Moreover, hospital rooms are often crowded, beds are often very close together, although to prevent the epidemic, patients should be separated at least by a distance of 1.5 meters.
Unfortunately you can also experience - added Karolina Böröcz - that in hospitals of less favorable economic situation is saved with disinfectants, there are few nurses and many patients and that is why there is a higher probability for infection.
In the opinion of Karolina Böröcz, where the appropriate preventive measures are followed, fewer infections of this type are recorded or the contagion of the pathogen can be stopped.
Government programme against MRSA
The treatment of MRSA infection is a huge expense for the National Health Insurance Fund, so in all countries it is fought against.
In England, for example, there is a government program to prevent and reduce MRSA cases.
Apparently the program is successful, according to the data provided, MRSA infections show a decreasing trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has among its priorities the prevention of multidrug-resistant agents (including MRSA) and hospital infections due to these pathogens.
Negative blood alcohol control of police commander who caused a fatal accident
The official expert report on the case of the fatal accident caused by the district XXII police commander has been made.
The possibility that the since resigned commander of the police of the XXII district, who on Tuesday ran over and caused the death of a passerby, drove drunk or in a stunned state can be excluded, said Attila Morvai, spokesman for the Attorney General of the Capital, after the expert report on the case had been prepared.
The expert report confirmed the result of the primary blood alcohol control that had already found that the former police commander did not consume alcoholic beverages before getting behind the wheel.
The then-chief of the district XXII police station, on Tuesday with his private vehicle as he turned to Kossuth Lajos street of the district XXII, ran over a 55-year-old man, who intended to cross the street, but not in the area designated for pedestrians.
(The latter fact, that the pedestrian did not use the zebra to cross the street, according to the regulations of the Traffic Code are not mitigating circumstances, the driver must always give way when folding.)
The passerby lost his life after being hospitalized.
The district police chief resigned and requested his retirement, according to the police statement, because he was very moved by the case.
The investigation of the case is carried out by the Budapest Prosecutor’s Office.
Attila Morvai also said that the former police commander from the outset collaborated with prosecutors in charge of the investigation.
