Bulgaria, the EU's real estate paradise
It is admirable the development of the Bulgarian real estate market - the attention of all Europe is directed towards that previously little mentioned Balkan country.
What, where and who buy in the EU’s even cheaper market, which will quickly become more expensive?
Analysis of the Bulgarian division of Re/Max.
The preferred target for real estate acquisitions in Eastern Europe is undoubtedly Bulgaria, with its cheap ski slope apartments and beach villas.
The mountainous regions of Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa are the most preferred, while on the beaches Albena, the "Golden Coast", the "Coast of the Sun", the old Sozopol and Nesebar, but more and more people are looking for properties also in the surroundings of Kavarna and Balchik.
According to the analysts of Re/Max in Bulgaria, sooner or later also the central area of the country - such as Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna - will arouse the interest of real estate developers and more and more people will buy properties in the especially cheap area of Rus.
The capital Sofia can also be attractive, as the commercial and office spaces promise a quick return on investment.
Bulgaria is on the best path to become one of the most attractive golf paradises in Europe, being able to be a prominent destination also during the other two seasons, in addition to summer and winter.
Therefore, cautious investors are already making their purchases, for example in the vicinity of Bansko.
In the opinion of analysts, those who buy real estate in Bulgaria are also striving to change their lives and their way of life.
Most of the customers are English, but they also come from France, Belgium, Spain and increasingly from Romania.
Maltese and Cypriot developers are also present and there are traditionally many Russian customers on the beaches of the Black Sea and in the ski paradises.
Foreign customers can be classified into three groups - says Georgi Jankov, regional director of Re/Max in Bulgaria.
Those who intend to settle here buy new or renovated properties for a price between <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>50 and <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>100,000 or old houses in poor condition between <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>5 and <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>15,000, to renovate them later.
They require good communication and access, and the proximity of a large city, shops and usually a local doctor is important to them.
The second category are the buyers of villas (Bulgaria in December was included among the top 10 holiday destinations of the Germans).
The third group are real estate investors who make their purchases in the hope of profiting in the medium or long term.
The price of capital real estate is constantly growing, as demand is increasing.
Although in the European Union Bulgaria has the lowest real estate prices, in the last five years these have suffered an annual increase of 21 percent.
The increase in the price of real estate considerably exceeds the growth of wages.
Fodor and the Six by Hundred Hungarians
According to the Minister of Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor, the expert level meetings will end on Tuesday and on Wednesday after the official inauguration will continue negotiations at ministerial level on the international climate regime after 2012.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world are deliberating on the Bali Roadmap on post-emission reduction efforts, set out in the Kyoto Protocol, in force until 2012.
At present, lively discussions on this issue are taking place between developing and industrialized countries.
The United States has already indicated that at the moment it does not want to negotiate on precise figures, although it tends to agree that compared to the situation in 1990, by 2020 the emission of gases responsible for the greenhouse effect will decrease by 25 to 40 percent.
Another major theme of the conference is whether or not industrialized countries, in addition to reducing emissions, are willing to provide material and technological aid to countries in need.
An agreement was also reached on the aid to be offered to developing countries.
The support fund, foreseen in the Kyoto Protocol, will be led by a 16-member board of directors, probably within the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF) - writes the "Piac és Profit".
The Six for Hundreds of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, Environment and Hydrology Minister Gábor Fodor supports the EU’s efforts to retain its leading role in global climate protection and to promote the signing of the new international agreement until 2009.
The minister stated that the EU commits to reduce its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 percent by 2020, compared to 1990 levels, regardless of whether or not the “post-2012 agreement” will be signed, and is willing to commit to a decrease of even 30 percent if the other large developed regions of the world and developing countries are also willing to make commitments in line with their responsibility and capabilities.
Gabor Fodor pointed out that the countries signatories to the 1997 Kyoto Protocol committed to decrease by 5.2 percent, within this the then 15 EU member states committed to comply with an 8 percent decrease.
Hungary's commitment is to reduce the emission of greenhouse gases responsible by 6 percent with respect to the period between 1985 and 87, which our country will meet - says the press release of the Ministry of Environment.
A lot is at stake in Bali, since within two years the UN will have to sign the international agreement on long-term climate policy, because if not, it is certain that its entry into force would be postponed to after 2012. In this case the reduction commitments, assumed in the Kyoto Protocol would not be immediately followed by a new international system of emission reduction, whose need was warned in its most recent scientific partnership that the IPCC Peace Prize is being dealt with.
With this, the reduction of emissions would be delayed and an increase of more than 2o C in the average temperature of the Earth could not be prevented, a fact that according to the scientists would have immeasurable and irreversible consequences.
The British Army Recruits on YouTube
British army units at a video distributor publish recordings of actions filmed in Iraq and Afghanistan to popularize themselves.
First the British Air Force (RAD) took advantage of YouTube services: special units displaced in Afghanistan since March 2006 are uploading videos about their actions against the Taliban, the BBC reported.
These recordings made with mini cameras mounted on the helmets are checked on the general body of operations of Kandahar, then sent to London to be uploaded to the Internet.
The political message is inevitable.
Already 139 recordings from air force soldiers have been uploaded in this way to the Internet and its "channel" has already been seen by more than 75,000 people.
The British Ministry of Defence was registered in the spring of 2007 under the name "defence headquarters" and publishes videos of both actions perpetrated in Iraq and Afghanistan, while both the Commonwealth Office and the multinational forces in Iraq (MNFI) have their own YouTube channel.
Operation in Afghanistan
Originally the air force had uploaded the videos with recruitment targets, but in the opinion of the Ministry of Defence they also serve to present to the public the true objective of the British army’s presence abroad.
This kind of propaganda costs practically nothing compared to conventional recruitment television spots – defence expert Gordon Mackenzie told the BBC – instead, they inevitably have some political message, since in a specific way they justify the reason for the military actions decided by the government.
The Americans prepared a video game
The army is also concerned by the fact that, in addition to the suspiciously edited and censored recordings, amateur videos appear in the distributor, for example on the death of soldiers: in the "official" propaganda films, a little hypocritical, the officers speak at most of losses, without presenting the bloody part of the fighting.
In addition, from the battlefields of Iraq and Afghanistan numerous videos recorded in real operations have been uploaded to the Internet, but the British military is only recently taking advantage of this opportunity.
Americans use a slightly different form for recruitment with freely downloadable shooting video games, called America's Army, in which in the middle of a more or less real situation the player can put himself directly in the place of the soldiers.
