"He was not in intervention but in patrol, and circulated at 40-50 km/h, without rotating headlight," explains a police source.
A green motorcycle of the Kawasaki brand, " not approved, i.e. not authorized to drive on public roads " (read below) and driven by two young men without helmets, was circulating " at full throttle " .
"He hit the police car on the left side, after a breach of the give way to the right," the police said.
Alcohol control on the occupants of the vehicle was negative.
The condition of the car (the front unraveled, windshield cracked, bumper torn off) testifies to the violence of the crash.
Very quickly, yesterday morning, the prosecutor of the Republic of Pontoise, Marie-Thérère de Givry, announced that he had entrusted an investigation for " acts of involuntary manslaughter and denial of assistance " to the IGPN, together with the departmental management of public security of Val-d'Oise.
In the afternoon, during a press conference, the prosecutor pointed out that the IGPN investigation, at this stage, ruled out the responsibility of the police.
According to the magistrate three witnesses of the accident, understood on Sunday afternoon, confirmed "the version of the police, namely that this minimoto bike arrived relatively quickly to his left ".
Yesterday, a type of groove, undoubtedly caused by the rubbing of the socks on the floor, showed that both vehicles had been stuck in the time for the police car to stop.
The vehicles have been confiscated and will be subjected to technical expertise.
The bodies of both victims were autopsied yesterday.
What happened right after?
Yesterday, a rumor circulated quickly in Villiers-le-Bel, according to which the policemen would have left the site very quickly, thus not providing relief to both young men.
The IGPN, being prudent, would also set aside " any serious misconduct " concerning this point.
"It's the most difficult aspect of the investigation, which needs more investigation, which you have to be very cautious about," a police source said.
Liberation found an eyewitness of these few moments that have followed the accident.
One of his windows that precisely leads to the scene.
“We went down right away, with my cousin who is a nurse at the hospital, to try to revive them,” said this witness.
There was nothing to do.”
Then he saw “a policeman who was completely terrified, limping.
Two others were trying to resuscitate one of the young men, the fourth was talking on the phone.”
Faced with the tension that quickly surrounded the scene, and, it seems, to the certainty that people were present of the unexpected situation of the young people, the policemen have been driven by colleagues who had arrived at the site.
According to this witness, relief arrived “about twenty minutes after the police marches.”
They also practiced heart massages, in vain.
" I will not assume that the police services did not provide assistance to the young people.
These young people have been rescued.
The firefighters arrived immediately.
Everything has been done to try to save them," the prosecutor said.
