Spectacular repair on the space station
It will have taken astronaut Scott Parazynski and his crewmates on the International Space Station (ISS) more than seven hours of work in space to make the spectacular repair of a torn solar panel indispensable for the continuation of the station’s scientific activities.
A risky departure that accumulated the records because of its duration, its distance from the habitable modules, the speed with which it has been imagined, instruments "chopped" by the astronauts to carry out the repair.
The problem appeared on Tuesday then that the astronauts had released from the shuttle Discovery the module Harmony, a thick cylindrical piece in charge of soon hosting the European and Japanese scientific laboratories (see picture).
This module is a type of landing platform for laboratory modules.
But you have to be able to supply them with electricity.
The second task of the crew was therefore to move an electricity production module with 17.5 tons solar panels, already present on the ISS, in order to put it in its final position.
After moving it, the crew began the reorganization of the module’s solar panels that have a wingspan of 76 meters.
And that’s where one of the panels, which are deployed as accordions, has been damaged by a little more than a meter or less by a cable that got stuck.
The deployment has been halted so as not to further damage the panel.
The astronauts, who initially had to make a control exit from the Discovery shuttle, and then go to repair another solar panel whose rotation system was faulty, were forced to devote themselves to the damaged panel.
And it is Scott Parazynski who has been chosen to go snail at the end of the 30-metre long remote control arm of the shuttle added to that of the station to carry out the repair.
He is one of NASA’s best spacewalkers.
Tall, sturdy, very skillful, has a highly developed torso and long arms.
At the age of 46, this doctor of training has been in charge of "operating" the "wounded" solar panel.
After having precisely inspected the damage, he sectioned the faulty cable and installed types of "tablets" in the damaged area.
He had been helped by the second " spacewalker " who had stayed close to the airlock and, from the interior, by other astronauts such as Peggy Whitson, the crew commander.
The tool he used, a mini hockey stick wrapped with insulator to prevent electrocution on the solar panels that produced several hundred volts, has been conceived and "scrambled" by the astronauts aboard the station.
Once the operation was over, Scott Parazynski waited for the panel to be fully deployed before taking inventory of his instruments and returning to the interior of the station.
Yesterday afternoon, the astronauts were taking advantage of a noon break before today, seven astronauts return from the Discovery shuttle for the return to Earth scheduled for Wednesday.
