A heavy memory
After more than 60 years of confidentiality, Bad Arolsen’s Nazi archives, which describe the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are openly accessible.
The 47 million archival documents, stored on 27 km of shelves in Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were not previously available only for a "humanitarian" purpose, i.e. individually and nominatively, at the request of a former victim or his rights-holders.
The eleven states in charge of its management - such as Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them to searchers and historians.
Since the process of ratification of this agreement by all States has been completed, the opening is effective since yesterday.
Sensitive information
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will allow searches "particularly on the displacements of prisoners, the population of the camps and the health status of forced workers," explains Reto Meistern, the director of these archives managed by the International Commission of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several States, such as Germany, were opposed to the opening of these nominative documents to the public, owing to the sensitive nature of certain information.
As well as the alleged homosexuality or mental handicap of certain victims of deportation.
The records of the concentration camps or of the arrest warrants established by the Gestapo had been gathered after the war for a practical purpose: to find the citizens deported or subjected to compulsory work and, eventually, to provide them with proof of their internment, in order to open the way to their compensation.
Still today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees handle tens of thousands of individual requests.
However, for a part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest.
"There is nothing fundamentally new to expect from these documents," said Professor Wolfgang Benz, director of the Research Center on Anti-Semitism at the Technische Universität Berlin in 2006.
