Will there be a year-end rally on the stock market? The experts, divided by the 'subprime' crisis.
With less than five weeks to go until the end of the year, investors are already rubbing their hands waiting for the traditional year-end rally to arrive.
However, this year the experts are not so clear that this is going to occur.
Banif believes that “from a statistical point of view, December on the stock market tends to be a positive month.
However, forecasts should not be based solely on statistics, especially because in the current context, uncertainties lurk in the markets, at least in the short term.
Although they are not supporters of the stock market catching a run in the last weeks of the year, these experts point out that "the stock market is sustained by the existence of liquidity, ready to invest given the lack of alternatives with guarantees, especially fixed income, affected by the effect of flight towards quality values both in the long and short sections".
Therefore, they believe that the stock market will have a rather lateral behavior, not exempt from volatility "especially because the impact of the likely fall in Fed rates is not known, given the high level of crude oil and the danger of stimulus from inflationary tensions."
Javier Barrio, BPI’s sales manager in Spain, agrees that this is not a good time to venture into saying that there will be a rally.
"It's not the thing for many joys," says the expert.
The Ibex has lost about 4% since its peaks on November 8 when the index closed at 15,945.7 points.
Yet not all experts have such a negative outlook.
Juan Solana, an analyst at Intermoney, believes that the Ibex 35 could close the year closer to 16,000 points thanks to the restructuring of the portfolios and the traditional contributions to the pension plans that occur every year at these dates.
However, the expert specifies that things will be somewhat different this year as he believes the rally will be ahead of the second week of December, after the Constitution bridge.
The analyst does not believe that volatility will affect the market trend.
For his part, Federico Olucha, analyst at Inversis Banco, says that we are close to technical levels and "we could therefore see a rebound of the index that could be boosted depending on the news coming from the United States in terms of the consequences of the crisis on the credit market".
The analyst is confident that these will be positive.
Analysts agree when choosing the values that will be responsible for taking the Ibex to new highs.
Solana, of Intermoney, says that "this year is about great values."
The expert would include in the portfolio the two big banks and some construction companies "because when the date comes, the electricity sector will be very expensive".
Meanwhile, Federico Olucha of Inversis Banco assures that the rises will come from the hands of the banking and the industrial sector.
The builders will also benefit from this rally, should they fail.
“ACS has been recovering positions for several months and we expect other construction companies such as Ferrovial and FCC to follow suit,” he said.
Cyclical consumption will be the protagonist in the latter part of the year due to the increase in sales in the holiday sales season.
On the other hand, the expert believes that the technology will also do very well although in this case there is not much representation in the Spanish market.
Five times in seven years
In the last seven years, on only two occasions December has been a bearish month.
The real end-of-year rally was in 2003, when the stock markets emerged from the crisis caused by the puncture of the technological bubble.
This year, in which the Ibex 35 recovered 28.17%, December recorded a rise of 6.68%.
We will have to see if 2007 is the fifth consecutive year of profits (for the moment the Ibex rises 8.36% since January) and if it can count on its end of year rally.
