What insurance is right for me?
Auto insurance, which covers the driver against possible claims, involves a significant expense that will depend on various factors, such as age, gender, age of the card, marital status, the type of vehicle to be insured or the use of it, among others.
Having a car is just the beginning.
Choosing the right car insurance is even harder than choosing the right car.
First of all, we need to be clear about what we are talking about.
Car insurance is an agreement between an insurance company and the insured.
This commitment is materialized in an insurance contract, which states that the company receives the value of the agreed premium in exchange for being responsible for the obligation to pay compensation in the event of a claim.
The premium is the price of insurance, which is established taking into account various factors, such as age, sex, age of the card, marital status, the type of vehicle to be insured or the use given to it, among others.
Insurance companies set their prices based on statistics, so that the more likely you are to suffer an accident, the higher the fee to be paid.
It is for this reason that both those over 25 and women have to pay lower premiums, as statistics show that they have a lower accident rate due to their prudence.
Also, using the counts, companies have concluded that married people tend to have fewer accidents than single drivers.
The use that is given to the vehicle will influence the frequency, and with it the probability of having some type of mishap.
Increasing the frequency increases the odds.
There are many variables that insurers take into account when setting the premium price.
That is why the driver must study the situation well to choose the car insurance that best fits his profile.
We will present here the most significant variables when choosing one or another type of insurance, so that it, in addition to adapting to the characteristics of the insured, offers a reasonable price.
Young people under 25 have several drawbacks when it comes to taking out insurance at an affordable price, such as reduced driving experience and seniority of the license.
Although the ideal to be well insured is full-risk insurance, there are other cheaper options.
The most cautious drivers can opt for an all-risk with franchise, so that they get the coverages of an all-risk insurance but at a more feasible price.
This type of agreement would mean that the customer pays a part of the amount of the loss.
"The portion of the amount of the claim that the customer provides will be pre-established according to the value of the premium, which will be higher the lower the amount," specifies Luis Noguera, top manager in Spain of First Europa, online insurance broker.
Another option is an extended third-party insurance, so that the customer ensures protection against damage caused to third parties, but not to those caused in their own car.
In addition, it would be covered by theft, fire and the loss of the vehicle.
One piece of advice.
If you are under 25, try to be careful and avoid claims as much as possible, as this will have an impact on the bonus, and may reduce the cost of insurance in the future.
A bonus is a reduction on the base rate that the company owns.
On the contrary, a penalty is a surcharge on that base rate.
“The bonuses and penalties will depend on the company and the company’s profit.
If the company has had a good year, it can afford to increase the bonuses," Noguera explains.
After the age of 25, drivers have it easier when hiring insurance, since the accident rate is reduced thanks to the accumulated experience.
For this reason, the most advisable is to contract an all-risk franchise.
"Normally young people can not make use of the experience previously acquired when relying on an accident, and even when driving," says the director in Spain of the European company, adding that most accidents occur in the second year of driving, once the 'novice fear' has passed.
However, if the client is married but still has no children it is preferable that he negotiates full-risk insurance, as long as his economic situation allows it, of course.
For their part, marriages with children are considered by insurers as the public with the lowest rate of accidents, so the surcharges will be lower.
In this case, the best insurance would be an all-risk insurance with a franchise (may be 300 euros), or, when a high bonus level is available, an extended third-party from the third year of life of the vehicle.
“They have a more relaxed drive and a greater purchasing power to afford to take on a larger amount of franchise,” said Luis Noguera.
For retirees, it is advisable to have an all-risk insurance with a franchise (this being 150 euros), or an extended third-party insurance when you have a high level of bonus.
It must be said that car insurance is important, not only because it covers the driver against possible claims, but also because it represents an important expense, which is why it is essential to properly study the insurance that suits us best according to our personal situation.
