The deterioration in rates can be explained in part by technical factors.
A change in the American People’s Bankruptcy Act (2005) resulted in a sharp drop in bankruptcy applications, which in turn represent a major loss on credit cards; the number of applications (and therefore, defaults) would be growing again, or it may happen that conditions for borrowers were getting worse.
The industry also reports strong payment rates, which show how much of its debts consumers pay each month.
And confidence in credit cards and asset-backed securities is pretty strong, despite paralysis in other financial areas.
Dennis Moroney of TowerGroup, a research firm, predicts that emission volumes for 2007 will be about 25 percent higher than last year.
The direct channels of infection of the crisis between subprime mortgages and the credit card market certainly exist: consumers like to charge debts to credit cards now that credit institutions are expiring.
But credit card issuers look more at cash flow than active securities, so falling prices don’t necessarily trigger a change in borrowers’ creditworthiness.
