Venus: twin brother of Earth.
Although its atmosphere is not suitable for life, Venus is the most Earth-like planet, something that had not been proposed so far. The European probe "Venus Express" discovered rays in the atmosphere and swirls at the poles, the same that also appear in winter on Earth.
For three decades, researchers had suspected that lightning could exist on Venus.
But now the European probe has brought new evidence: it discovered electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere. On Venus the rays shut down from a height of 54 kilometers from one cloud and behind another, Cris Russell of the University of California in Los Angeles tells the scientific journal "Nature".
According to the famous Urey-Miller model of the origin of life, lightning caused life on Earth: storms could have caused reactions in the ocean that, in turn, would have given rise to the amino acids that are the basic components of life.
On Venus it’s not like that: if there was ever life there, that would have to be in one of the earliest states of evolution,” explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today, there can be no life on the surface of Venus: the atmospheric pressure is almost 100 times higher than on Earth and temperatures of 500°C reign on the surface, oscillating in such a way that temperatures below zero can be reached.
“Possibly, Venus is a ‘diabolical’ twin of Earth, but it’s still a twin,” Russell said.
The main goal of the Venus Express mission is to answer the question of why Venus, so similar to Earth in mass and size, has had such a different evolution.
Since there were no special missions since the 1990s, only for research of this planet, the launch of "Venus-Express" in November 2005 was a very important step for Venus research.
The latest results of the research that will be presented in many articles of "Nature", in the opinion of the researchers, underline not only the uniqueness of Venus in the Solar System.
"This also demonstrates that neighboring planets have more common features with Earth than we had assumed," ESA reports.
Despite the already known stormy winds at the North Pole, the researchers discovered in the south polar region also a vortex formed by the clouds that rotates faster.
This phenomenon is reminiscent of wind flows in the upper atmospheric layers of the Earth’s poles, as described by a team of researchers led by Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Institute of Special Astrophysics and Space Physics.
The second planet in the Solar System has the mass almost equal to Earth and with its equatorial diameter of 12,000 kilometers it is almost as large.
This planet also called the Dawn Star or Evening Star orbits the Sun for nearly 225 days.
But its rotation period is slower: one day on Venus equals 243 days on Earth.
Although Venus with its surface temperatures of 460 degrees and its atmospheric pressure of 92 bars does not closely resemble Earth, scientists assume that both planets had formed under the same conditions.
On both planets water had agglomerated that on Earth remained in the oceans, but on Venus it was dissociated in the universe.
While on Earth carbon dioxide had become carbon stones, on Venus it forms most of the atmosphere.
